---
<Layout title="Taal and Rhythm for Harmonium | Harmonium Halt"
  description="Master the rhythmic framework of Indian music and how harmonium fits within taal cycles. Free harmonium lesson with interactive web harmonium tool.">
  <div class="bg-white border-b" style="border-color:rgba(28,16,8,.08)">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-2.5 breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a><span class="mx-1.5">›</span>
      <a href="/lessons">Lessons</a><span class="mx-1.5">›</span>
      <span>Taal and Rhythm for Harmonium</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 sm:py-12">
    <div class="mb-6 sm:mb-8">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 mb-4">
        <span class="badge badge-intermediate capitalize">intermediate</span>
        <span class="text-xs" style="color:rgba(28,16,8,.4);font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">⏱ 35 min · Intermediate</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="section-title text-2xl sm:text-3xl lg:text-4xl mb-3" style="color:#1c1008">Taal and Rhythm for Harmonium</h1>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed" style="color:rgba(28,16,8,.6);font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">Master the rhythmic framework of Indian music and how harmonium fits within taal cycles.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl p-4 sm:p-5 mb-6 border" style="background:#fef9f0;border-color:rgba(212,146,10,.25)">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-sm mb-3" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">📌 Key Takeaways</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1.5">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Taal = fixed rhythmic cycle that repeats continuously</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Teentaal = 16 beats — the most common taal</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Sam = beat 1 — the most important beat</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Keherwa = 8 beats — used for bhajans</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Develop internal rhythm before playing with tabla</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-hm">
      <h2>What is Taal</h2>
      <p>Taal (rhythmic cycle) is the foundation of all Indian music. Like a wheel that keeps turning a taal repeats its fixed pattern continuously throughout a performance. The harmonium player must always know where they are within the taal — which beat which section and crucially where the Sam (first beat) is. Losing the taal is one of the most serious musical errors.</p>

      <h2>Teentaal — 16 Beats</h2>
      <p>Teentaal is the most important taal with 16 beats divided into 4 sections of 4 beats: Dha Dhin Dhin Dha bar Dha Dhin Dhin Dha bar Na Tin Tin Ta bar Ta Dhin Dhin Dha. The first beat (Dha) is Sam — the point of resolution. Practice clapping Teentaal while playing Sa on each Sam. Once comfortable add simple scale playing within the taal framework.</p>

      <h2>Keherwa — 8 Beats</h2>
      <p>Keherwa has 8 beats: Dha Ge Na Ti Na Ka Dhi Na. It is the standard taal for bhajans folk songs and devotional music. If you have ever clapped along to a bhajan you were likely feeling Keherwa or a variant. Practice Keherwa by tapping your foot on beats 1 and 5 (Sam and midpoint) while playing simple bhajan melodies.</p>

      <h2>Playing with a Metronome</h2>
      <p>Before playing with a tabla develop your internal rhythm using a metronome set to 60 BPM. Practice scales and alankars strictly in time never rushing or slowing. The metronome is your most honest teacher showing exactly where your rhythm wavers. Students who develop metronomic precision progress far faster when they eventually play with tabla.</p>

      <h2>Harmonium with Tabla</h2>
      <p>When playing with tabla listen actively and lock your playing to the tabla player's beat. On Sam both instruments must arrive together cleanly — this requires anticipating Sam slightly before it arrives. Practice by clapping Teentaal with your left hand while playing Sa Re Ga patterns with your right hand. This builds simultaneous rhythm and melody awareness.</p>

    </div>
    <div class="mt-8 mb-6">
      <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-xl sm:text-2xl mb-3" style="color:#1c1008">Practice Now</h2>
